Nice 'n' quick, easy to pull off to the side of the road and find where I am and where I need to go without losing much time. Voice-guided directions are clear and give ample time to prepare for turns (except for some very specific large intersections during rush hour, lol) - also, love the real-time notifications for traffic, construction, speed traps, etc, and the fact that the app automatically re-routes if I miss my turn. Really ENJOY the "Your Places" menu, especially the "Upcoming" section which shows the places from your google calendar events!!!  3. Travel history needs to be made  useful for users and shown in a nicely formatted  monthly mileage report! Not just a timeline, but a downloadable report with each trip and the mileage.  That would be GREAT!"  Seeing visited points on a map is useless!! 4. Consistency in spoken distance measurements would help. I would prefer if it always said 1.4 miles or .5 miles. text: i have used map since when i got my first galaxy phone my first galaxy phone was and still is an excellent gps navigation software the only reason i give my first galaxy phone a star is that over time there appears to be some fraying at the seam first starting approximately around the time of the ore release the application has bloated to the point that the application now take exceptionally long to load and the application has become generally very sluggish the application still work great once the application start second voice navigation over bluetooth is now partly broken though this may be because of ore is issue with the older bt standard rather than the application itself specifically the voice instruction truncated over bt unless there is another application that keep bt active grin playing music via an application or running some of the aps designed to work around this problem
original_text: I have used Maps since 2013 when I got my first Galaxy phone.  It was and still is an excellent gps navigation software.  The only reason I give it a 4 star is that over time, there appears to be some fraying at the seams.  1.  First, starting approximately around the time of the Oreo release, the app has bloated to the point that it now takes exceptionally long to load and it has become generally very sluggish.  It still works great once it starts.  2. Second, voice navigation over bluetooth is now partly broken (though this may be because of Oreo's issues with the older BT standards rather than the app itself).  Specifically, the voice instructions truncate over BT unless there is another app that keeps BT active (e.g. playing music via an app or running some of the apps designed to work around this problem).
